# Testing strategy

## Phase 0 (current)

- Rust: unit smoke tests per module (`module_name()` or minimal logic).
- Integration test in `lib.rs` wiring all modules.
- CI: `cargo test`, `cargo fmt --check`, `cargo clippy`.
- Frontend: `pnpm typecheck`, `pnpm lint` — no E2E yet.

## Phase 1+

Add CLI binaries for isolated manual testing:

```bash
cargo run --bin test-audio -- record 3s output.wav
cargo run --bin test-stt -- input.wav
cargo run --bin test-inject -- "Hello world"
```

Each module ships tests in `mod.rs` or `tests/` subdirectory.

## What to test where

| Module | Unit | CLI | Integration |
|--------|------|-----|-------------|
| audio | buffer format, sample rate | record/play WAV | pipeline start/stop |
| stt | prompt building | transcribe file | end-to-end FR phrase |
| inject | clipboard restore logic | paste to Notepad | hotkey -> inject |
| hotkey | key mapping parse | register/unregister | toggle dictation |
| store | CRUD, migrations | dump config | history roundtrip |
| pipeline | state transitions | — | full dictation path |

## CI expectations

- All unit tests pass on Ubuntu (fast feedback).
- `tauri build` matrix on Windows, macOS, Linux (compile-only).
- No flaky network-dependent tests in default CI.

## Anti-patterns

- Do not skip tests for "stub" modules — keep smoke tests until real logic lands.
- Do not add Playwright/Cypress in Phase 0–1; manual Notepad test is the Phase 1 done criteria.
